\f1\b \cf0 \ul \ulc0 FARMING
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
\
A key reason why so many non-huum stay in Saskantinon despite its somewhat confusing and even harsh political environment is 
\f1\b agriculture
\f0\b0  does well, relatively speaking, in the region. And this is due almost largely to the fact that the Dauni Vakasaquas have learned, since the Catastrophe, how to take the place of birds and bees. They spread this knowledge throughout the Lands and continue to ensure the food supply.\
\
Nearly all of the towns and villages in the area maintain farming operations at one level or another of technological advancement.  Many farmers are free-holders, but work within larger collective groups. In the South, the Dauni Vakasaqua syndicates act as a kind of farmers cooperative. Many others are more-or-less vassals who work to support the nearest town and its institutions.  While the technological level is fairly rudimentary in many areas, the land is fertile enough to support a variety of techniques. \
\
Domesticated non-sint livestock for milk and cloth (fur) materials is fairly common. Using livestock for food is less common and somewhat controversial, especially outside of the Northern provinces.\
\
Mammalian meat plays a considerably smaller role in Saskan life than it does in our world. Pigs, cows, hares and other species all have sint and mixed cousins who look very unkindly on eating their relatives and feel it is a threat (and not only from huum carnivores).  There are no avians of any type, hence no chickens, etc.  Most meat-eating is aimed at fish, reptiles and insects.   \
\

\f1\b \ul AGRICULTURAL RESOURCES and ECONOMIC STRATA
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
\
Farming and agriculture in the Saskan Lands are difficult and labor intensive. Have been so for centuries.  Elements of prototypical capitalism are evident in several trades. But that is not the case in agricultural work. Some level of private enterprise and corporatism occur in hunting, fishing and harvesting of reptiles and insects. But planting, pollinating, harvesting and caring for the crops, as well as milling, distribution and so on requires coordination, planning and effort well beyond the capabilities of the small-scale Saskan market systems. For example, large-scale stores for hard times are an important feature of the agricultural system.  Many of the Afflicted class are engaged for part of the year in this type of work.  They are basically a landless peasantry who work in exchange for subsistence food stuffs, which are provided year-round. \
\
All of the major institutional players have a role in coordinating the agricultural systems. The Dauni Vakasaqua and the Outer Land tribes tend to have the most humane approaches to employing the Afflicted. The Helioptics less so, especially when it comes to non-huum populations.  The role of the Riders organizations, the Empafarasi, the Eelani and other western tribes, as well as the Kahila, in managing the agricultural systems and work relationships lies somewhere in between.\
\
\

\f1\b \ul LAND
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
\
Though free-holding is common, it is a kind of lease or tenure relationship.  Land "ownership" is general is not thought to be something that an individual or family group can actually do.  There are seldom actual private and individual claims to permanent land sovereignty.  Where it is not in the trust of a local organization or guild or tribe or clan, it is often managed by a collective, which often have existed for centuries, and treated as a  shared equity resource.\
\
This is a reality that grew out of necessity. Due to the manually intensive nature of much agricultural work, it is exceedingly difficult for a small producer or individual owner to make a success at it. Many genetic lines have no solid intellectual or cultural tradition of "private ownership" in any case.\
\
Only in the Weir Lands controlled by the Empafarsi has the idea of "lordship" over land begun to emerge. In the Runes of Bye and the Nye Lands, and to a lesser extent in Mobalbesq, there are centuries-old land tenures held by various clans, which nearly amount to sense of "ownership", but this seldom devolves down to the level of individuals or nuclear families.  In the Kahila Lands, particularly the Kahilakol, the idea of land "ownership" is utterly anathematized through long tradition of open and collective use of the forests and other commons.  \
\
\

\f1\b \ul HUNTING and FISHING
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
\
The region supports grazing and hunting, especially in the North.  \
\
Both a pastoral and nomadic economies exist in these areas, though nomadic/traveling bands are less common than settled ones, particularly when it comes to fishing. \
\
Domestication of livestock is much more common in the huum regions of the North than in the South, the Outer Lands or the West. But even there, it is the source of ongoing disputes. Violent conflicts have erupted over the centuries between animal-liberationists and huum-supremacists, often triggered by arguments over meat-eating and management of animals as "stock".  This is not a wholly Huum vs. Sint issue either. There are carnivorous sints.\
\
A variety of wild beasts who are 
\f2\i not
\f0\i0  sentient \'96 in the sense that they do not use tools, use a language intelligible to other species, create urban or village centers, or develop an oral or written literature \'96 roam the plains and mountains, especially in the northern, eastern and southern regions outside of the Ring. \
\
Hunting expeditions, most often -- but not exclusively -- organized by huum or huum-appearing guilders, work these areas.  They gather and hunt in the western mountains and the river basins too, as well as in the coastal areas, although there tends to be much less available prey in those areas. \
\
Fishing is common in both rivers and seas, with occasional disruptions from water-resident sints from the Krbsh Sea.\
\
Fishing and sea-going trades are very common in the Eastern provinces. Fishing tends to be a more organized and more pastoral enterprise than hunting, with regular groups fishing specific shore-lines or off-shore areas.  As with hunting, this type of work can be fraught with difficulties and conflict due to the large number of fully sentient animals inhabiting the Delta of Ilyushan as well as the Krbsh Sea itself.  Typically, they themselves are consumers of seafood, so -- as with land-based meat-eating -- the overall picture is not a simple one. \
\
As far as conflicts go, it is often more a matter of competition between groups than it is an ethical question.\
\
\

\f1\b \ul MINING
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
\
Mining operations are located mainly in the western mountains, as well as near the marshy Krbsh Sea shoreline of the southeastern Arq speaking region.  \
\
\

\f1\b \ul MANUFACTURING
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
\
Most manufacturing is at a fantasy-world-medieval level, with a focus on small-scale handicraft. Aside from the large-scale agricultural efforts, there are few large manufactories too. \
\
Common types of goods include:\
- Prepared foods, food ingredients\
- Prepared and fermented beverages\
- Weapons and Armor\
- Clothing and fabrics\
- Conveyances (wagons, boats, and so on)\
- Tools and Hardware\
- Rope and Sails\
- Cut stone and wood\
- Medicines and psycho-active substances\
- Musical instruments\
- Scrolls, parchments, books and writing materials\
- Pigments and brushes\
- Candles, Lamps and Reflective surfaces (mirrors)\
- Utensils and Containers\
\

\f1\b \ul SERVICES
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
\
With the exception of agricultural goods, the provisioning of most goods and services is dominated by guild monopolies, though there are competing guilds and geographical variations.  Intellectual work -- writing, philosophy, science, history, theology and so on -- tend to be invested in long-standing institutions like the various Scribes Guilds, which are more or less arms of the various power centers, and the Academy at Terpinol.\
\
See notes below on Trade.\
\
Key service industries are also coordinated through guilds, though some are very loose. These include:\
- Scribes\
- Innkeepers\
- Brooders\
- Dauni Vakasaquas (botanists, collective farmers, herbalists)\
- Healers and Scanners\
- Finders (detectives and thieves)\
- Guards / Volunteers / Watchers, etc. (cops and army)\
- Riders (protection)\
- Bards and Actors\
- Carpenters\
- Miners\
- Sailors\
- Advocates\
