\f1\b \cf0 \ul Exchange Rates, Prices, Money Supply
\f0\b0 \ulnone \
\
(Needs more...)\
\
Guild-related prices are set centrally everywhere except in the Outer Lands, though this is subject to both good communications and a willingness to obey the center. Prices of agricultural goods fluctuate from season to season. Open-air markets usually permit open bargaining. In Helioptic areas where the authorities 'suggest' certain price ranges and in the South the powerful agricultural co-ops exert peer pressure to normalize prices. \
\
Money supply is directed by what are effectively central banks and mints in Borded and Beshquahoek, with the Byenung Board of Accountable Governance for the Oversight of Fair Trade and the Security of Exchange, working with the Night Hall, acting as an important central bank as well. The Byenung Board doesn\'92t issue currency, but they do collect it, along with other rarities, as they call them, and hold them as backing for their letters of credit and their hard chits.  Whether they actually have hoarded enough to fully pay out should there ever be a run on chits is not known. \
\
There is nothing like a stock exchange. Investments in a shipping adventures are handled directly with the concerned parties in the East/ The Night Hall network facilitates such communications.  A rough kind of commodities market occurs in several southern and eastern locales when ships arrive in port, at fall harvest time and in mid-spring, when buyers arrive to bid for goods, grain, herbs, when large shipments arrive at key river cities, and so on. The largest ones occur in Borded, Qurol, Rut\'f3nik, Byenung, Selaron, Morilly and Ingar. Agricultural prices can vary for vegetables and fruits, but grain prices are set centrally and, to a large extent, grain is itself a kind of currency.\
